nexttext:
Since the correlation function $\left\langle{\boldsymbol{\sigma}_1^L \!\cdot \!\boldsymbol{\sigma}_1^R}\right\rangle$ is always finite varying between 0 and -3 (see Fig.~\ref{fig2}(a)-(b)), both $\widetilde{W}_{irr}$ and   $\partial_K (\Delta \widetilde{W}^2)$ diverge at the critical point in the thermodynamic limit. Moreover, $\Delta \widetilde{W}^2$ takes its maximum slightly before $K_c$ where $\partial_K (\Delta \widetilde{W}^2)=0$. This coincides with $\left\langle{\boldsymbol{\sigma}_1^L \!\cdot \!\boldsymbol{\sigma}_1^R}\right\rangle=-1$ which is the point at which the two impurities start to get entangled. Although in some previous works \cite{bayat-TIKM-12,cho2006} this was considered to signal the iQPT, we see that for large values of $J'$ the onset of entanglement slightly precedes $K_c$.

\section{Comment on out-of-equilibrium quantities}
In the previous sections we have considered both the irreversible work and the variance of work, respectively Eq.~(\ref{E.Wirr}) and Eq.~(\ref{E.WVar}),  as a means to investigate the out-of-equilibrium thermodynamics of the quenched TIKM. In this Section we would like to emphasise that both the irreversible work, given by Eq.~(\ref{Wirr_nor_Corr}), and the variance of work, given by Eq.~(\ref{Delta_W2}), are truly out-of-equilibrium quantum thermodynamic quantities, although evaluated at equilibrium due to the sudden small-quench approximation. In fact, for quasi-static processes, the irreversible work would result identically null as the work equals the free energy difference,

and the work PDF would be a delta function peaked at the energy difference between the pre- and post-quenched ground states, resulting thus in a PDF with zero variance. Instead, in the sudden quench case, which approximates the case where the quench is performed at a rate much faster than the typical time evolution scale of the pre-quenched ground state, both quantities give a measure of the irreversibility by performing the quench~\cite{Jarzynski07,PlastinaetalPRL14}.

As an additional comment about the out-of-equilibrium nature of these quantities, note that, whereas a temperature can be associated  to the initial state (which is $T=0$ in our analysis), the same does not hold after the quench has been performed, notwithstanding the small, but finite, amplitude and/or the specific time dependence of the adopted protocol, as long as the quench is not performed infinitely slow.


\section{Conclusion}
In this article we have considered the fluctuations of the work performed on a two-impurity Kondo spin chain when the coupling between the impurities is instantaneously varied. We have numerically shown that both irreversible work and work variance, as non-equilibrium quantities, signal the impurity quantum phase transition between the Kondo and RKKY regimes. Both quantities 
exhibit scaling at the quantum critical point, and allows for known equilibrium critical exponents to be extracted.  In addition, a new critical exponent $\kappa$, governing the behavior of the rescaled irreversible work at the phase transition, is brought to light. Importantly, all out-of-equilibrium quantities considered are amenable to experimental observation in solid-state nanostructures or in systems of ultracold atoms  or trapped ions, since ultimately it is sufficient to measure a two-point  spin correlation function.



